TY  - JOUR
T1  - Better Stories, Not Better Constructs, To Generate Better Theory: A Rejoinder to Eisenhardt
AU  - Dyer, W. Gibb
AU  - Wilkins, Alan L.
Y1  - 1991/07/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1991.4279492
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1991.4279492
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 613
EP  - 619
VL  - 16
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this article the authors discuss an article published in a pervious issue that presented an approach to building better theory through the use of case studies. The authors suggest that the paper does not do enough to support the claim that the methods used surpass pervious methods for conducting case studies. They compare the author's approach with various case studies and discuss the limitations of the author's work. Their main concerns fall into three areas; the in-depth study of a single case, deep vs. surface description and the telling of good stories vs. the creation of good constructs. They assert that by not conducting the in-depth research applied in a traditional case study the author is depriving the research of the insight one receives from that depth of study.
AB  - In this article the authors discuss an article published in a pervious issue that presented an approach to building better theory through the use of case studies. The authors suggest that the paper does not do enough to support the claim that the methods used surpass pervious methods for conducting case studies. They compare the author's approach with various case studies and discuss the limitations of the author's work. Their main concerns fall into three areas; the in-depth study of a single case, deep vs. surface description and the telling of good stories vs. the creation of good constructs. They assert that by not conducting the in-depth research applied in a traditional case study the author is depriving the research of the insight one receives from that depth of study.
